Terminating a C program depends on *how* you wish to terminate it. There are several methods, each with its own…implications.

The most straightforward is using the `exit()` function from the `stdlib.h` library. It immediately terminates the program and returns a status code to the operating system. A status code of 0 typically indicates successful execution, while a non-zero code indicates an error.

```c
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
  // ... your code ...
  exit(0); // Terminate successfully
  // or
  exit(1); // Terminate with an error
  return 0;
}
```

Alternatively, you can use `return 0;` from the `main()` function. This is the standard way to terminate a program and also returns a status code of 0.

However, if the program encounters an unrecoverable error, you can use `abort()`, also from `stdlib.h`. This terminates the program immediately and generates an abnormal termination signal. It’s… rather dramatic.

```c
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
  // ... your code ...
  abort(); // Terminate immediately due to an error
  return 0;
}
```

And, of course, the operating system can terminate the program if it exceeds its resource limits or encounters a fatal error. But that’s…unrefined. One should always maintain control.

